window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"The science of life is referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"Anatomy","B":"Biology","C":"Ecology","D":"phylogeny"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Biology is the scientific study of life and living organisms. It involves the study of structure, function, growth, origin, evolution, and distribution of living organisms. The other options do not accurately define the science of life. Anatomy is the study of the structure of organisms and their parts; ecology is the study of the interactions between organisms and their environment; and phylogeny is the study of the evolutionary history and relationships among individuals or groups of organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The epidermis of a leaf is considered an example of a tissue because the cells","images":[],"options":{"A":"allow sunlight to pass through","B":"are covered by waxy cuticle","C":"all possess a similar structure and function","D":"allow water pass through them by osmosis"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A tissue is a group of cells that have a similar structure and act together to perform a specific function. In the case of the epidermis of a leaf, the cells all possess a similar structure and function, which is to protect the leaf and prevent water loss. The other options are characteristics of the epidermis but do not explain why it is considered a tissue.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"The organism at the organ organisation of life is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Euglena","B":"Spirogyra","C":"Ginger","D":"Tapeworm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Euglena and Spirogyra are at the cellular level of organisation    Ginger is an advanced plant which at the organ level of organization.    Tapeworm has organ and organ system.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"The disadvantage of complexity of organisation in the higher organisms is that it leads to","images":[],"options":{"A":"mutual interdependence between component cells","B":"internal structural specialization","C":"increased adaptation to environment","D":"slower rate of diffusion of oxygen to individual cells"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The complexity of organization in higher organisms does lead to a slower rate of diffusion of oxygen to individual cells. This is because in complex organisms, cells are not in direct contact with the external environment, and oxygen has to travel a longer distance to reach each cell. This is not a disadvantage per se, as complex organisms have developed efficient circulatory systems to overcome this. However, among the given options, this is the most accurate. The other options are not disadvantages but rather characteristics or advantages of complex organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"In which of the following multicellular organisms is interdependence of cells maintained?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Spirogyra","B":"Volvox","C":"Endocrine","D":"Pandorina"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Interdependence of cells is maintained in Volvox. Volvox is a type of green algae that forms spherical colonies of up to 50,000 cells. They live in a variety of freshwater habitats, and were among the first examples of multicellular organisms. Each cell in a Volvox colony is interconnected to other cells by strands of cytoplasm, allowing them to coordinate their movements and function as a single organism. Spirogyra is a filamentous green algae, but it does not form colonies like Volvox. Endocrine is a system in animals, not a multicellular organism. Pandorina is a green algae that forms colonies, but the cells are not as interconnected as in Volvox.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Which of the following processes occurs in the second phase of meiosis?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Homologous chromosomes separate","B":"Two daughter cells are formed","C":"Fertilization occurs","D":"Segregation of genes occurs"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The second phase of meiosis is called meiosis II, which is similar to mitosis. In this phase, the sister chromatids of each chromosome separate and move to opposite poles of the cell. This is what is referred to as 'Homologous chromosomes separate'. The other options are incorrect. Two daughter cells are formed at the end of meiosis I, not II. Fertilization is not a part of meiosis, it is a separate process that can follow meiosis in sexual reproduction. Segregation of genes occurs in the first phase of meiosis (meiosis I), not the second.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"The muscle cell fluid of an athlete was tested immediately after a 100m race and was found to contain a high concentration of lactic acid. Explain what could have caused this. The","images":[],"options":{"A":"athlete must have eaten food containing lactic acid just before the race","B":"athlete must have injected lactic acid into his blood just before the race","C":"athlete's muscle must have carried out anaerobic respiration during the race","D":"athlete must have inhaled lactic acid from the environment during the race"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During intense physical activity like a 100m race, the body's demand for energy exceeds the oxygen supply. This causes the muscles to switch from aerobic respiration (which requires oxygen) to anaerobic respiration (which doesn't require oxygen). Anaerobic respiration in muscles produces lactic acid, which can build up in the muscle cells, causing the high concentration observed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"The graph beside represents the growth pattern of an animal. Which of the following groups of animals shows this pattern of growth?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Cestoda","B":"Reptila","C":"Amphibia","D":"Insecta"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Insecta shows this pattern of growth. Growth in insects is usually regular.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"The pulmonary circulation involves movement of the blood to and from the","images":[],"options":{"A":"brain","B":"kidneys","C":"liver","D":"lungs"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Pulmonary circulation is the portion of the cardiovascular system which carries deoxygenated blood away from the heart, to the lungs, and returns oxygenated (oxygen-rich) blood back to the heart.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The table below shows the blood composition of four individuals.  Blood Composition/IndividualPlasmaRed blood cellsWhite blood cellsPlateletsI NormalNormalHighNormalIINormalNormalNormalNormalIIINormalNormalLowNormalIVNormalNormalNormalLow   Use the information contained in the table to answer this question    Which of the individuals is likely to be suffering from haemophilia?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When the blood platelets in an organism is low, the blood clots slowly.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : TOWARDS BETTER HEALTH","question":"The table below shows the blood composition of four individuals.  Blood Composition/IndividualPlasmaRed blood cellsWhite blood cellsPlateletsI NormalNormalHighNormalIINormalNormalNormalNormalIIINormalNormalLowNormalIVNormalNormalNormalLow   Use the information contained in the table to answer this question  Which of the individuals is likely to have HIV?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"III. A person with low white blood cells won't have enough lymphocytes to fight against infections and they will be prone to many illnesses including HIV.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"A student dissecting an animal specimen discovered that it had two auricles and one ventricle. The animal is likely to be a/an","images":[],"options":{"A":"fish","B":"reptile","C":"amphibian","D":"bird"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The heart of an amphibian has two auricles and one ventricle. The two auricles receive blood from the two different sources (the body and the lungs/gills), while the single ventricle pumps the blood out of the heart. This is different from the hearts of fish (which have one auricle and one ventricle) and reptiles and birds (which have two auricles and two ventricles).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"The diagrams above are parts of a human lung. Which of the labelled parts is diagram Z taken from?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"II","B":"III","C":"IV","D":"V"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The labelled part IV is where diagram Z is taken fromIV.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"The diagram beside is an illustration of the human excretory system. Which of the labelled parts contains the highest amount of nitrogenous waste?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"IV","D":"VI"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The part labelled I contains the highest amount of nitrogenous waste","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Increasing adrenaline content of the blood would be expected to decrease the flow of blood to the","images":[],"options":{"A":"liver","B":"heart","C":"lungs","D":"brain"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Adrenaline: it prepares the body for fright, decreases the rate at which blood flows to the heart.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The following are all examples of a simple reflex action except","images":[],"options":{"A":"swallowing","B":"sneezing","C":"walking","D":"blinking"},"answer":"C","explanation":"- Walking is usually done in a way which is not rapid.    - Walking is a voluntary action that we think about first before doing.    - Walking  usually  involves numerous neurones.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"Impulses are conducted towards the nerve cell through the","images":[],"options":{"A":"myelin sheath","B":"dendrons","C":"axons","D":"synaptic nodes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a neuron, impulses are conducted towards the nerve cell through the dendrites (also known as dendrons). The dendrites are the branched projections of a neuron that act to propagate the electrochemical stimulation received from other neural cells to the cell body, or soma, of the neuron from which the dendrites project. The myelin sheath, axons, and synaptic nodes are involved in the transmission of the impulse away from the cell body.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"The function of the convex lens in the correction of eye defects is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"diverge light rays from far objects to focus image on the retina","B":"converge light rays to focus image behind the retina","C":"converge light rays to focus the image before the retina","D":"converge light rays from far objects to focus their image on the retina"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The convex lens is used in the correction of long sightedness in order for light rays to converge from far objects and focus their image on the retina.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Which of the following parts of the eye contains light sensitive cells?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Choroids","B":"Iris","C":"Retina","D":"Lens"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The retina is the part of the eye that contains light-sensitive cells. These cells, known as photoreceptors, convert light into electrical signals that can be interpreted by the brain. There are two types of photoreceptors: rods, which are sensitive to low light levels and provide black-and-white vision, and cones, which are responsible for color vision and detail. The other options, the choroids, iris, and lens, do not contain light-sensitive cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REGULATION OF INTERNAL ENVIRONMENT (HOMEOSTASIS)","question":"The hair on the human skin will stand erect when the person is","images":[],"options":{"A":"in an air-conditioned room","B":"strolling in the sun","C":"taking a hot drink","D":"doing strenuous exercise"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A fall in body temperature stimulates the following processes to produce and conserve heat    - Vasoconstriction    - Sweating (little)    - Increasing metabolic rate    - Raising Hairs","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"When fertilization occurs that leads to formation of a zygote, which of the following processes takes place?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The tail of the sperm fuses with the egg cell","B":"Both tail and head of the sperm fuse with the egg cell","C":"The nucleus of the sperm fuses with the egg cell","D":"The egg cell develops on its own without the sperm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During fertilization, the nucleus of the sperm cell fuses with the nucleus of the egg cell to form a zygote. The tail of the sperm does not fuse with the egg cell, it only helps the sperm to move towards the egg. The head of the sperm contains the nucleus which carries the genetic material. Therefore, the correct answer is that the nucleus of the sperm fuses with the egg cell.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Which of the following structures in a flower develops into the seed?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Testa","B":"Integument","C":"Ovule","D":"Ovary"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a flower, the ovule develops into the seed after fertilization. The ovule is the part of the ovary of the seed plant where the egg cell is formed. After fertilization, the ovule develops into a seed. The other options are incorrect because the testa and integument are parts of the seed, not the structures that develop into the seed, and the ovary develops into the fruit, not the seed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"An illustration of a human male reproductive system is shown beside. Which of the labelled parts can be cut to ensure permanent sterility?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The vas deferens could be cut to ensure permanent sterility.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"EVOLUTION : ADAPTIVE COLOURATION","question":"The brightly coloured petals in some plants is an adaptive colouration for","images":[],"options":{"A":"feeding","B":"pollination","C":"dispersal","D":"shedding"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The brightly coloured petals in some plants are an adaptive colouration for pollination. The bright colours attract pollinators like bees, butterflies, and birds, which then transfer pollen from the male parts of the flower to the female parts, facilitating fertilization. The other options are incorrect because the petals do not play a direct role in feeding, dispersal, or shedding.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Squirrels easily kill some trees because","images":[],"options":{"A":"they inject poisonous substances into the trees","B":"most trees are susceptible to squirrels bites","C":"they feed voraciously on the roots.","D":"they gnaw the bark and destroy them"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Squirrels can cause damage to trees by gnawing on their barks. This can lead to the tree's death as the bark serves as a protective layer for the tree. When this layer is damaged, it exposes the tree to diseases and pests. The other options are incorrect because squirrels do not inject poisonous substances into trees, not all trees are susceptible to squirrel bites, and squirrels do not feed on tree roots.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The major role played by accessory pigments during photosynthesis is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"add colour to plants but not to trap light energy","B":"trap light energy that chlorophyll cannot absorb","C":"transfer energy from chlorophyll to other pigments","D":"prevent chlorophyll from absorbing unnecessary light"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Accessory pigments, such as carotenoids and phycobilins, absorb light wavelengths that chlorophyll cannot absorb effectively. This broadens the range of light wavelengths that can be utilized for photosynthesis, thereby increasing the overall efficiency of light energy capture by the plant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The main raw materials required for photosynthesis are","images":[],"options":{"A":"oxygen and water","B":"oxygen and carbon dioxide","C":"oxygen and chlorophyll","D":"carbon dioxide and water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the help of chlorophyll pigments. The main raw materials for photosynthesis are carbon dioxide and water. Carbon dioxide is obtained from air through the stomata while water is obtained from the soil through the roots.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"What is the benefit of thunder and lightening to farmers?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Addition of nitrates to the soil","B":"Aeration of the soil","C":"Removal of harmful bacteria from the soil","D":"Addition of rain water to the soil"},"answer":"A","explanation":"During a thunderstorm, the high temperatures and pressure caused by lightning cause the nitrogen in the air to react with oxygen, forming nitrates. These nitrates are then carried to the ground by rainwater, enriching the soil with nitrogen. This process is beneficial to farmers as nitrogen is a vital nutrient for plant growth.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following substances must be present in the soil for growth of a healthy green plant?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amino Acids","B":"Carbon","C":"Glucose salts","D":"Magnesium ions"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Magnesium ions must be present in the soil for the growth of a healthy green plant. Magnesium is a vital nutrient for plants as it is a part of chlorophyll, the compound that plants use for photosynthesis to produce food. It is also used in the creation of DNA, RNA and proteins. The other options, Amino Acids, Carbon, and Glucose salts, while important, are not necessarily required from the soil as plants can produce or obtain them through other means.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"The purpose of proteins in the diet of a mammal is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"promote growth and repair cells","B":"break down molecules","C":"regulate the flow of chyme","D":"serve as co-factors for enzymes"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The purpose of proteins in the diet of a mammal is to promote growth and repair cells. Proteins are essential nutrients for the human body. They are one of the building blocks of body tissue and can also serve as a fuel source. As a fuel, proteins provide as much energy density as carbohydrates. The other options, while related to functions of proteins, are not the primary purpose of proteins in the diet of a mammal.  Protein can be found in foods like:    seafood.  eggs.  lean meat.  beans.  peas.  nuts.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Excess carbohydrates can be stored in the muscles in the form of","images":[],"options":{"A":"cellulose","B":"glycogen","C":"Chitin","D":"lipids"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Excess carbohydrates in the body are stored as glycogen in the liver and muscles. Glycogen is a form of energy storage readily available for use by the body when needed. It is not stored as cellulose or chitin as these are structural components of plant and fungal cells respectively, and not used for energy storage in humans. Lipids are a form of long-term energy storage but are not the primary form of carbohydrate storage.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"The bones of the legs of a six year old boy are observed to be weak and crooked. Which of the following elements were deficient in his mother's diet at pregnancy?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Sodium and Iron","B":"Iron and manganese","C":"Calcium and phosphorus","D":"Magnesium and sulphur"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The bones of a six-year-old boy being weak and crooked indicates a deficiency in calcium and phosphorus. These two elements are essential for bone health and development. Calcium is the main component of bones and teeth, and phosphorus works with calcium to build strong bones and teeth. Deficiencies in these nutrients can lead to bone deformities. Sodium, iron, manganese, magnesium, and sulphur, while important for other bodily functions, are not primarily responsible for bone health.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : MICROORGANISMS IN ACTION","question":"The diagram beside is an illustration of an experimental set-up to test the action of yeast. What test would be used to confirm the nature of the gas given off  at I?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Insert a glowing splint","B":"Pass the gas through lime water","C":"Insert a piece of litmus paper","D":"Smell the gas"},"answer":"B","explanation":"- A fermentation process will take place and which will lead to the evolution of carbon(IV)oxide.    - Lime water is a reagent that absorbs CO2","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following digestive enzymes  would be greatly affected if the liver fails to produce bile?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amylase","B":"Cellulose","C":"Lipase","D":"Protease"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Bile, produced by the liver, plays a crucial role in the digestion and absorption of fats in the small intestine. The enzyme that breaks down fats (lipids) is Lipase. If the liver fails to produce bile, the activity of Lipase would be greatly affected because bile emulsifies fats, increasing the surface area for Lipase to act upon. Therefore, the digestion of fats would be greatly affected.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : FEEDING HABITS","question":"The appropriate food to be given to the child in the picture above is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"beans","B":"garri","C":"bread","D":"avocado pear"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The child is deficient of protein; Beans is a source of protein.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following food substances will have little or no calorific value?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Proteins","B":"Carbohydrate","C":"Lipids","D":"Water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Calorific value refers to the amount of energy that can be obtained from a substance when it is completely burned. Among the options given, water has no calorific value because it does not undergo combustion and hence does not release energy. Proteins, carbohydrates, and lipids all have calorific values as they can be metabolized to release energy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"A space containing a group of interactive organisms is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"community","B":"habitat","C":"ecosystem","D":"population"},"answer":"C","explanation":"An ecosystem refers to a community of living organisms in conjunction with the nonliving components of their environment, interacting as a system. These biotic and abiotic components are linked together through nutrient cycles and energy flows.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"The area around the earth where life activities go on is referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"biosphere","B":"lithosphere","C":"habitat","D":"ecosystem"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The biosphere is the global sum of all ecosystems. It can also be termed as the zone of life on Earth, a closed system (apart from solar and cosmic radiation and heat from the interior of the Earth), and largely self-regulating.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"The following are abiotic components of the ecosystem except","images":[],"options":{"A":"bacteria","B":"topography","C":"water","D":"wind"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Abiotic components of an ecosystem are the non-living physical and chemical elements in the environment. These include elements such as sunlight, temperature, wind, water, soil and atmospheric gases. Bacteria, however, are living organisms and are therefore not considered abiotic components of an ecosystem. They are part of the biotic components which include all living organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following instruments would be most appropriate in comparing the air pressure at different places in a habitat?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Hygrometer","B":"Barometer","C":"Photometer","D":"Air pressure disc"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A barometer is an instrument used to measure atmospheric pressure. It can be used to forecast short term changes in the weather, to determine altitude, and to help in creating surface weather analysis maps. Therefore, it would be the most appropriate instrument for comparing the air pressure at different places in a habitat. A hygrometer measures humidity, a photometer measures light intensity, and an air pressure disc is not a recognized instrument for measuring air pressure.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Study the diagram below and use it to answer this question      The best title for the above diagram is","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"terrestrial food web","B":"terrestrial food chain","C":"aquatic food chain","D":"aquatic food web"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The diagram is a food web that comprises terrestrial organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Study the diagram below and use it to answer this question    How many food chains are in the diagram?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Three","B":"Four","C":"Five","D":"Six"},"answer":"C","explanation":"We have 5 food chains in the food web    1. Grass \u2192 Grasshopper \u2192 Toad \u2192 Snake \u2192 Hawk \u2192 Man    2. Grass \u2192 Grasscutter \u2192 Man    3. Grass \u2192 FieldMouse \u2192 Snake \u2192 Hawk \u2192 Man    4. Grass \u2192 Goat \u2192 Lion \u2192 Man    5. Grass \u2192 FieldMouse \u2192 Hawk \u2192 Man.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Plants with breathing roots are characteristic features of vegetation in","images":[],"options":{"A":"tropical grassland","B":"temperature grassland","C":"salt water swamp","D":"tropical rain forest"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Breathing roots, also known as pneumatophores, are a type of root that protrudes above the ground in some plant species. They are found in swampy or marshy environments where the soil is waterlogged and oxygen levels are low. These roots grow upwards out of the water or ground to access the oxygen in the air. This is a characteristic feature of vegetation in salt water swamps.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"Study the diagram of the zones of a marine habitat below and use it to answer this question      In which of the zones can very few organisms be found?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"D","explanation":"IV is called the benthic zone, which is characterised with the presence of cold dark waters with very few living organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Study the diagram of the zones of a marine habitat below and use it to answer this question    Which of the following factors exerts a major effect on the distribution of living organisms in the habitat?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Salt","B":"pH","C":"Light","D":"Rainfall"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Light is necessary for photosynthesis, a process that is vital for life on Earth. Since plants cannot grow in the absence of light, it affects their distribution. This inturn affects the distribution of organisms that are directly or indirectly associated with the green plants.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : POLLUTION OF THE ATMOSPHERE","question":"The use of water closet and septic tanks is preferred to use bucket and pit latrines because","images":[],"options":{"A":"it is cost effective","B":"contaminated faeces are completely kept away from flies","C":"the water for flushing contains chlorine which kills germs","D":"it prevents flies from breeding"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The use of water closets and septic tanks is preferred to bucket and pit latrines because they are more sanitary. In these systems, human waste is flushed away with water into a septic tank, where it is stored and broken down by bacteria. This keeps the waste completely isolated from the environment, preventing flies from coming into contact with it and spreading diseases. Therefore, the statement that 'contaminated faeces are completely kept away from flies' is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : PUBLIC HEALTH","question":"The detection of vibro cholera in public drinking water is a sign of","images":[],"options":{"A":"clean water","B":"outbreak of disease","C":"water pollution","D":"decayed organisms in the water"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Vibrio cholerae is a bacterium that causes cholera. It is usually found in water or food sources that have been contaminated by feces from a person infected with cholera. Hence, the detection of Vibrio cholerae in public drinking water is a sign of water pollution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : FACTORS THAT AFFECT POPULATION","question":"Which of the following factors would be least likely to act as a density dependent limiting factor in a population of mice?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Build up of waste products","B":"Predation","C":"Parasitism","D":"Unfavourable climate"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Parasitism would least act as a density dependent limiting factor","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"The primary cause of species endangerment is","images":[],"options":{"A":"disappearing habitats","B":"increase in temperatures","C":"acid rain","D":"exposure to hazardous wastes"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The primary cause of species endangerment is disappearing habitats. This is because when habitats disappear, species lose their homes and the resources they need to survive, such as food, water, and shelter. This can lead to a decrease in population size and eventually, endangerment. The other options, while they can contribute to species endangerment, are not the primary cause.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"The following pairs of traits are examples of continuous and discontinuous variations respectively except","images":[],"options":{"A":"eye colour and body weight","B":"height and blood group","C":"skin colour and fingerprints","D":"body weight and tongue rolling"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Continuous variation is a type of variation that has no limit on the value that can occur within a population. Examples include height, weight. Discontinuous variation is a type of variation in which an individual either has a characteristic or they do not. Examples include blood group, tongue rolling. Eye colour is an example of discontinuous variation, not continuous.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>51","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following statement is true about the ABO blood group system?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Antigens are located on the surface of white blood cells","B":"Antibodies are located in the blood plasma","C":"Antibodies are located on the surface of red blood cells","D":"Antigens are located in the blood plasma"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In the ABO blood group system, antigens are located on the surface of red blood cells, not white blood cells or in the plasma. These antigens are what determine a person's blood type (A, B, AB, or O). Antibodies, on the other hand, are located in the blood plasma. They are proteins that the immune system uses to identify and neutralize foreign objects, such as bacteria and viruses. If a person with type A blood (which has type A antigens) were to receive type B blood (which has type B antigens), their immune system would recognize the type B antigens as foreign and would attack them with antibodies. This is why it's important to match blood types for transfusions.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>52","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The classes of fingerprints in man are","images":[],"options":{"A":"whorl, alternate, opposite and compound","B":"compound, loop, whorl and alternate","C":"whorl, arch, compound and loop","D":"arch, simple, compound and opposite"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The three basic classes of fingerprints are loops, whorls, and arches. These categories are based on the patterns that the ridges on the fingertips make. Loops have one or more ridges entering from one side, curving, then going out on the same side they came in. Whorls have one or more ridges making a complete circuit. Arches have ridges that enter on one side and exit on the other. The option 'whorl, arch, compound and loop' is the closest to the correct answer, although 'compound' is not a standard category of fingerprint. It's possible that 'compound' is being used here to refer to fingerprints that have characteristics of more than one category.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>53","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"Which of the following diseases is transmittable through genes?","images":[],"options":{"A":"HIV/AIDS","B":"Sickle cell anaemia","C":"Diabetic","D":"Presbyopia"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Sickle cell anaemia is a genetic disease that is passed down through families in which red blood cells form an abnormal crescent shape. It is caused by an abnormal type of hemoglobin called hemoglobin S. Hemoglobin is a protein inside red blood cells that carries oxygen. It is not a disease that is transmitted through contact or environment but through genes from parents to offspring.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>54","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"Two plants with red flowers were back crossed, which of the following results indicate that the plants are heterozygous red flowers, where red flowers are dominant?","images":[],"options":{"A":"75% red and 25% white","B":"50% red and 50%white","C":"100% white","D":"100% red"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In genetics, a backcross (BC) is a cross between a hybrid and one of its parents or an individual genetically similar to its parent. If two heterozygous (Rr) plants (where R represents the dominant red allele and r represents the recessive white allele) are crossed, the expected phenotypic ratio would be 75% red and 25% white. This is because three out of the four possible combinations (RR, Rr, rR) would result in red flowers, while only one combination (rr) would result in white flowers.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>55","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"In the structure of DNA, which of the following statements is true?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The double helix are held together by covalent bonds","B":"Nucleotide is made up of ribose, phosphate and an organic nitrogen compound","C":"Guanine is the opposite of cytosine","D":"Adenine is the opposite of cytosine"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In the structure of DNA, the statement 'Guanine is the opposite of cytosine' is true. This is because in the DNA structure, the nitrogenous bases pair up in a specific way: Adenine (A) pairs with Thymine (T), and Guanine (G) pairs with Cytosine (C). This is known as complementary base pairing. The other options are incorrect. The double helix in DNA is held together by hydrogen bonds, not covalent bonds. Nucleotides in DNA are made up of deoxyribose, not ribose. Adenine is not the opposite of cytosine; it pairs with thymine.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>56","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"In a case of complete dominance, what is the phenotypic ratio of the cross Bb x Bb; where B = black and b = white?","images":[],"options":{"A":"1 black : 1 grey : 2 whites","B":"1 black : 3 whites","C":"1 black : 2 blues : 1 white","D":"3 blacks : 1 white"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In a case of complete dominance, the phenotypic ratio of the cross Bb x Bb is 3 blacks : 1 white. This is because in a Punnett square for this cross, three of the four possible combinations (BB, Bb, and bB) would result in the dominant phenotype (black), while only one combination (bb) would result in the recessive phenotype (white). The other options do not correctly represent the phenotypic ratio for this cross.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>57","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"Two yellow-flowered hybrid plants each carrying a recessive factor for flowers with green colour were crossed. Which of the following ratios shoes the correct proportion of offspring that have green flowers?","images":[],"options":{"A":"2 in 2","B":"1 in 3","C":"1 in 4","D":"1 in 5"},"answer":"C","explanation":"This is a classic Mendelian genetics problem. When two heterozygous (hybrid) organisms are crossed, the offspring will exhibit a 3:1 ratio of dominant to recessive traits. In this case, the yellow flower color is dominant and the green color is recessive. Therefore, 1 in 4 offspring will have green flowers.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>58","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"What name is given to a sudden change in a gene or chromosome?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Allele","B":"Genotype","C":"Mutation","D":"Phentype"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Mutation is the changing of the structure of a gene, resulting in a variant form which may be transmitted to subsequent generations, caused by the alteration of single base units in DNA, or the deletion, insertion, or rearrangement of larger sections of genes or chromosomes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>59","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : RELEVANCE OF BIOLOGY TO AGRICULTURE","question":"Bees are of great importance to the farmer because they","images":[],"options":{"A":"provide him with honey","B":"pollinate flowers","C":"sting crop pest to death","D":"destroy flowers by sucking nectar from them"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Bees are of great importance to farmers because they help in the pollination of flowers. Pollination is the transfer of pollen from the male parts of a flower to the female parts of a flower of the same species, which results in fertilization and the production of seeds. Bees, as they move from flower to flower in search of nectar, inadvertently carry pollen on their bodies and thus aid in this process.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2012>60","subject":"Biology","year":"2012","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following sequences is the correct evolutionary trend in plants?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Algae \u2192 Liverworts \u2192 mosses \u2192 ferns","B":"Liverwort \u2192 mosses  \u2192 ferns \u2192 algae","C":"Mosses \u2192 algae \u2192 ferns \u2192liverworts","D":"Ferns \u2192 liverworts \u2192 mosses \u2192 algae"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Algae are thallophytes which has simple structure than the liverworts and moss which are bryophytes. It should be noted that ferns are trichophytes  (Vascular plants) which tend to be more complex than algae and bryophytes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];